{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
'''Most Faithful Majesty''' ({{lang-pt|Sua Majestade Fidelíssima}}) was the title used by the [[Portuguese monarch]]s, from 1748 to 1910.

The sobriquet '''Most Faithful King''' ([[Latin]]: ''Rex Fidelissimus'', Portuguese: ''Rei Fidelíssimo'') was a title awarded by the [[Pope Benedict XIV]] – as spiritual head of the [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic Church]] – in 1748, to the King [[John V of Portugal]] and to his heirs. 

The title ''Fidelissimus'' remains attached to monarchs descended from whoever received the original sobriquet. The sobriquet can be awarded to either a king or a queen. The only European monarchy that has received the sobriquet was the now-defunct monarchy of Portugal. 

